{
  "What is the difference between distance and displacement?": "",
  "Distance is total path length (scalar), displacement is straight-line change in position (vector)": "",
  "Displacement is always larger than distance": "",
  "They are the same thing measured differently": "",
  "Distance has direction, displacement does not": "",
  "Distance measures the total length of the path traveled (scalar, always positive). Displacement measures the straight-line distance from start to finish with direction (vector, can be positive, negative, or zero).": "",
  "What is average speed?": "",
  "Total distance traveled divided by total time taken": "",
  "Final speed minus initial speed": "",
  "The speed at a single instant": "",
  "Total displacement divided by total time": "",
  "Average speed = total distance / total time. It is a scalar quantity and is always positive.": "",
  "What is average velocity?": "",
  "The velocity at one instant": "",
  "Total distance divided by total time": "",
  "The sum of all velocities divided by the count": "",
  "Displacement divided by total time taken": "",
  "Average velocity = Δx / Δt (displacement / time). It is a vector quantity and can be positive, negative, or zero.": "",
  "A car travels 100 km north then 100 km south. What is its distance and displacement?": "",
  "Both are 200 km": "",
  "Distance = 200 km, displacement = 0 km": "",
  "Both are 100 km": "",
  "Distance = 0 km, displacement = 200 km": "",
  "Distance is the total path: 100 + 100 = 200 km. Displacement is the net change in position: 100 km north − 100 km south = 0 km (back to start).": "",
  "What is instantaneous speed?": "",
  "The maximum speed reached": "",
  "The speed of an object at a specific moment in time": "",
  "The speed at the start of a journey": "",
  "The average of all speeds during a trip": "",
  "Instantaneous speed is the rate of distance change at a particular instant. It corresponds to the magnitude of the slope of a position-time graph at that point.": "",
  "Can a moving object have zero velocity?": "",
  "No — a moving object always has velocity": "",
  "Not instantaneously while moving, but an object can have zero average velocity after a round trip": "",
  "Yes — if it moves in a circle forever": "",
  "Only at the speed of light": "",
  "An object completing a round trip has zero average velocity (zero displacement / time). However, at any instant during motion, instantaneous velocity is nonzero. At a turnaround point, instantaneous velocity momentarily equals zero.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of speed?": "",
  "Meters per second (m/s)": "",
  "Kilometers per hour (km/h)": "",
  "Miles per hour (mph)": "",
  "Feet per second (ft/s)": "",
  "The SI unit of speed (and velocity) is meters per second (m/s). Other units like km/h can be converted: divide by 3.6 to convert km/h to m/s.": "",
  "A jogger runs 5 km in 25 minutes. What is their average speed in km/h?": "",
  "12 km/h": "",
  "5 km/h": "",
  "0.2 km/h": "",
  "25 km/h": "",
  "Average speed = distance / time = 5 km / (25/60 h) = 5 / 0.417 = 12 km/h.": "",
  "What does the slope of a position-time graph represent?": "",
  "Acceleration": "",
  "Distance": "",
  "Velocity": "",
  "Force": "",
  "The slope of a position-time graph gives velocity. A steeper slope means higher velocity; a horizontal line means zero velocity (stationary). A negative slope indicates motion in the negative direction.": "",
  "An object moves 30 m east in 5 s. What is its velocity?": "",
  "150 m/s east": "",
  "25 m/s east": "",
  "6 m/s east": "",
  "6 m/s (direction unknown)": "",
  "Velocity = displacement / time = 30 m east / 5 s = 6 m/s east. Since velocity is a vector, the direction must be included.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes distance?": "",
  "The straight-line separation between two points": "",
  "Displacement measured without direction": "",
  "The total length of the path traveled by an object, regardless of direction — a scalar quantity": "",
  "The area under a velocity-time graph": "",
  "Distance is scalar (no direction) and equals the sum of all path segments. It is always positive or zero and can never decrease during motion.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes displacement?": "",
  "The total length of the path an object travels during its motion, measured along every twist and turn — a scalar quantity": "",
  "The change in position of an object measured as a straight line from initial to final position, with direction — a vector quantity": "",
  "The rate at which an object changes its location over a given time interval, expressed in meters per second — a kinematic rate": "",
  "The product of an object's average speed and the elapsed travel time, yielding the total ground covered — measured in meters": "",
  "Displacement = Δx = x_final − x_initial. It has magnitude (shortest distance between start and end) and direction. It can be positive, negative, or zero.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes speed?": "",
  "The rate at which an object covers distance — a scalar quantity equal to distance divided by time": "",
  "The magnitude of displacement per unit time — a vector quantity that includes the direction of travel along the path": "",
  "The product of distance and the time elapsed during motion, measured in meter-seconds as a compound kinematic unit": "",
  "The instantaneous rate of change of displacement, accounting for both the magnitude and the direction of the motion": "",
  "Speed = distance/time. It is always positive or zero, has no direction, and tells how fast (but not in what direction) an object is moving.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes velocity?": "",
  "Acceleration multiplied by time": "",
  "Speed with an arbitrary direction assigned": "",
  "The rate at which distance is covered": "",
  "The rate of change of displacement with respect to time — a vector quantity with both magnitude and direction": "",
  "Velocity = Δx/Δt. As a vector, it includes direction. Positive and negative signs indicate opposite directions along a chosen axis.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes instantaneous velocity?": "",
  "The velocity of an object at a single specific moment in time, equal to the derivative of position with respect to time": "",
  "The peak velocity an object reaches during its entire journey, representing the single fastest point along its motion path": "",
  "The total displacement divided by the total elapsed time of travel, giving the overall rate of position change for the trip": "",
  "The reading obtained exclusively from a calibrated speedometer device, which only measures how fast the vehicle is currently going": "",
  "Instantaneous velocity v = dx/dt, the limit of Δx/Δt as Δt → 0. It is the slope of the tangent to the position-time curve at any given instant.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes uniform motion?": "",
  "Motion at constant velocity — traveling in a straight line at an unchanging speed with no acceleration": "",
  "Motion in a circular path at constant speed": "",
  "Motion that gradually speeds up": "",
  "Any motion along a straight line": "",
  "Uniform motion means constant velocity: zero acceleration, constant speed, and constant direction. On a position-time graph, it appears as a straight line.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a reference frame?": "",
  "A coordinate system used to define positions and describe the motion of objects relative to an observer": "",
  "The fixed physical boundary that separates one region of measurable space from another, often established by a visible landmark": "",
  "The designated initial position from which all timed experiments begin, serving as the universal agreed-upon zero point": "",
  "The downward vertical direction established by the local gravitational field, which determines how all free objects accelerate": "",
  "A reference frame provides the axes and origin from which positions, velocities, and accelerations are measured. Motion is always described relative to a chosen reference frame.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a position-time graph?": "",
  "A graph showing the distance between two objects over time": "",
  "A map showing where an object is located": "",
  "A graph with velocity on the y-axis and time on the x-axis": "",
  "A graph that plots an object's position on the vertical axis against time on the horizontal axis, where the slope represents velocity": "",
  "Position-time graphs encode motion information: slope = velocity, horizontal line = stationary, curved line = changing velocity. They are fundamental tools in kinematics.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the odometer vs. speedometer distinction?": "",
  "An odometer measures displacement while a speedometer measures velocity": "",
  "An odometer measures total distance traveled (scalar), while a speedometer measures instantaneous speed (scalar)": "",
  "Both measure the same quantity in different units": "",
  "An odometer measures average speed while a speedometer measures maximum speed": "",
  "The odometer accumulates total path length (distance — always increasing). The speedometer shows how fast the car is going right now (instantaneous speed). Neither provides directional information.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes relative velocity?": "",
  "The total velocity of all objects in a system": "",
  "The maximum velocity difference between two objects": "",
  "The velocity of one object as observed from the reference frame of another moving object": "",
  "The average of two objects' velocities": "",
  "Relative velocity v_A relative to B = v_A − v_B. If two cars move in the same direction at 60 km/h and 40 km/h, the relative velocity of the first from the second's frame is 20 km/h.": "",
  "A student walks 4 blocks north to school, then 3 blocks east to the library after school. Her pedometer (step counter) shows she walked 700 m total. What are her distance and displacement from home to the library?": "",
  "Distance = 500 m (the hypotenuse of the path), Displacement = 700 m at 53.1 degrees north of east (the actual walked route)": "",
  "Distance = Displacement = 500 m, since both quantities always measure the shortest straight-line route between two locations": "",
  "Distance = 700 m (total path), Displacement = 500 m at 36.9° east of north (the straight-line shortcut)": "",
  "Distance = Displacement = 700 m, because both quantities always give the total path length that the person walked on foot": "",
  "Distance is the 700 m total path (4 blocks + 3 blocks). Displacement is the straight-line distance from home to library. If blocks are 100 m: displacement = √(400² + 300²) = 500 m at tan⁻¹(300/400) = 36.9° east of north.": "",
  "A delivery driver drives 30 km in 30 minutes, stops for 15 minutes for a delivery, then drives 30 km back in 30 minutes. Calculate the average speed and average velocity for the entire trip.": "",
  "Average speed = 48 km/h (total distance 60 km / total time 1.25 h); average velocity = 0 (displacement is zero since he returned to the start)": "",
  "Average speed = 0 because the driver returned to the start; average velocity = 48 km/h based on total distance of 60 km divided by total time of 1.25 h": "",
  "Average speed = average velocity = 48 km/h, since the total distance traveled was 60 km and the total elapsed time was 1.25 hours for the whole trip": "",
  "Average speed = average velocity = 0, because returning to the starting point means both the distance traveled and the displacement are zero for the trip": "",
  "Total distance = 30 + 30 = 60 km. Total time = 30 + 15 + 30 = 75 min = 1.25 h. Average speed = 60/1.25 = 48 km/h. Displacement = 0 (returned to start), so average velocity = 0/1.25 = 0.": "",
  "A GPS app shows a driver has traveled 50 km using 'trip distance' but the 'displacement' reading shows only 30 km. What does this difference reveal about the driver's path?": "",
  "Displacement is always exactly 60% of distance": "",
  "The driver went backwards at some point, which subtracted from distance": "",
  "The GPS is malfunctioning": "",
  "The driver did not travel in a straight line — the path included turns, curves, or detours, making distance > displacement": "",
  "Distance ≥ |displacement| always. They are equal only for straight-line motion without backtracking. The 20 km difference (50 − 30) indicates the path deviated significantly from a straight line between start and end points.": "",
  "A sprinter runs 100 m in 10.0 s. Her coach says her average speed was 10 m/s but her instantaneous speed at the 50 m mark was 11.5 m/s. How is this possible?": "",
  "She must have been running downhill at the 50 m mark which artificially raised her instantaneous speed beyond the average — on flat ground they would be equal values": "",
  "The coach made a measurement error because instantaneous speed at any point during a uniform-distance run must exactly equal the average speed over the whole race": "",
  "Instantaneous speed must always be identical to average speed for any straight-line motion — the higher reading at the 50 m mark was caused by a faulty timing device": "",
  "Her speed varied during the race — she accelerated from rest at the start and was faster than average in the middle; instantaneous speed at a point can differ from average speed over the whole race": "",
  "Average speed = total distance / total time = 100/10 = 10 m/s. But she started from rest and accelerated, so she was slower at the start and faster later. At the 50 m mark, her instantaneous speed exceeded the average. Instantaneous ≠ average unless speed is constant.": "",
  "Two trains leave the same station. Train A travels north at 80 km/h and Train B travels south at 60 km/h. After 2 hours, what is the distance between them and why does this involve vectors?": "",
  "280 km apart — since they travel in opposite directions, their displacements add: (80 × 2) + (60 × 2) = 160 + 120 = 280 km": "",
  "4800 km apart — to find separation you multiply the two speeds and then by time: (80 times 60) times 2 = 4800 km of total separation distance": "",
  "140 km apart — averaging the two speeds and multiplying by time gives the gap: ((80 + 60) / 2) times 2 = 140 km between the trains": "",
  "40 km apart — subtracting velocities gives the relative approach speed: (80 minus 60) times 2 = 40 km of total separation between the trains": "",
  "Train A displacement: 160 km north. Train B displacement: 120 km south. Since they move in opposite directions, the separation = 160 + 120 = 280 km. Vector addition: 160 north − (−120 south) = 160 + 120 = 280 km.": "",
  "A car's speedometer reads 90 km/h due north. At that instant, the driver turns onto an eastbound highway and maintains 90 km/h. Has the velocity changed?": "",
  "No — speedometers measure velocity directly": "",
  "Yes — the speed increased because east is a 'faster' direction": "",
  "Yes — although the speed remained constant at 90 km/h, the direction changed from north to east, so the velocity (a vector) has changed": "",
  "No — the speed stayed the same so the velocity is unchanged": "",
  "Velocity is a vector (magnitude + direction). Speed (magnitude) stayed at 90 km/h, but direction changed from north to east. Therefore the velocity changed, which means the car experienced acceleration during the turn.": "",
  "An ant walks along a meter stick from the 20 cm mark to the 80 cm mark, then back to the 50 cm mark. What are the distance and displacement?": "",
  "Distance = Displacement = 60 cm": "",
  "Distance = 30 cm, Displacement = 90 cm": "",
  "Distance = 90 cm (60 cm forward + 30 cm back); Displacement = +30 cm (from 20 cm to 50 cm mark)": "",
  "Distance = 60 cm, Displacement = 0 cm": "",
  "Distance: |80 − 20| + |50 − 80| = 60 + 30 = 90 cm. Displacement: final − initial = 50 − 20 = +30 cm (toward the higher numbers on the stick).": "",
  "A race car on a 5 km circular track completes exactly 3 laps in 6 minutes. What are its average speed and average velocity?": "",
  "Average speed = average velocity = 150 km/h, since speed and velocity are always identical for any object moving along a circular track path": "",
  "Average speed = 150 km/h (15 km / 0.1 h); Average velocity = 0 (displacement is zero after complete laps, back to start)": "",
